{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}} '''Amlaíb mac Sitriuc''' ("Amhlaeibh, son of Sitric") or '''Olaf Sigtryggsson''' was the son of [[Sigtrygg Silkbeard]], the [[Hiberno-Norse]] [[King of Dublin]], and [[Sláine ingen Briain|Sláine]], the daughter of [[Brian Boru]]. A member of the [[Uí Ímair]] dynasty, his ancestors also included [[Amlaíb Cuarán]] and [[Gormflaith ingen Murchada|Gormflaith]], who were influential in medieval Ireland. He was held to ransom by the Gaelic [[Kings of Brega|lord of Brega]] and later killed in England by [[Anglo-Saxons]] while on his way on [[pilgrimage]] to Rome in 1034.<!--Hudson, p 83--> Some of his descendants later became the [[Kings of Gwynedd]] in Wales.
==Life==
===Family=== Amlaíb was the son of the ruling King of Dublin, [[Sigtrygg Silkbeard]] (d. 1042), and his wife [[Sláine ingen Briain|Sláine]], daughter of the [[King of Munster]] and [[High King of Ireland]], [[Brian Boru]] (d. 1014), and his first wife.<ref name="Hudson83">Hudson, p 83</ref><ref name="Hudson83"/><ref name="Annals13-819">{{cite web |url=http://www.ucc.ie/celt/online/T100005B/text013.html |title=Part 13 of the Annals of the Four Masters |publisher=[[University College Cork]] |work=[[Annals of the Four Masters]] |page=819 |accessdate=10 March 2009 }}</ref><ref name="MacManus278"/> His paternal grandfather was [[Amlaíb Cuarán]] (d. 981), the powerful [[Kings of Jórvík|King of York]] and of Dublin.<ref name="Hudson83"/> Amlaíb Cuarán's wife was [[Gormflaith ingen Murchada|Gormflaith]] (d. 1030), a "beautiful, powerful and intriguing Irish woman" who later married Boru at the same time Sigtrygg married Sláine.<ref name="MacManus278">MacManus, p 278</ref>
Amlaíb had four half-brothers: Artalach (d. 999),<ref name="ODNB">{{cite ODNB |id=25545 |title=Sihtric (Sigtryggr Óláfsson, Sigtryggr Silkiskegg) (d. 1042)|first=Benjamin T.|last=Hudson}}</ref> Oleif (d. 1013), Godfrey (d. 1036), Glúniairn (d. 1031).<ref name="Hudson83"/> Oleif was killed in immediate vengeance for the burning of the Norse city of [[Cork (city)|Cork]].<ref name="Annals11">{{cite web |url=http://www.ucc.ie/celt/online/T100005B/text011.html |title=Part 11 of the Annals of the Four Masters |publisher=[[University College Cork]] |work=[[Annals of the Four Masters]] |page=769 |accessdate=10 March 2009 }}</ref> Glúniairn was killed by the people of [[Kings of Brega#Kings of Lagore/Deiscert Breg (South Brega)|South Brega]] in 1031.<ref name="Annals13-823">{{cite web |url=http://www.ucc.ie/celt/online/T100005B/text013.html |title=Part 13 of the Annals of the Four Masters |publisher=[[University College Cork]] |work=[[Annals of the Four Masters]] |page=823 |accessdate=10 March 2009 }}</ref> Godfrey was killed in [[Wales]], possibly by a first cousin.<ref>Hudson, p 82</ref> Amlaíb was outlived by his half-sister Cellach, who died in 1042 in the same month as her father.<ref name="Annals14-843">{{cite web |url=http://www.ucc.ie/celt/online/T100005B/text014.html |title=Part 14 of the Annals of the Four Masters |publisher=[[University College Cork]] |work=[[Annals of the Four Masters]] |page=843 |accessdate=10 March 2009 }}</ref>
===Politics=== In 1027, after the death of Máel Sechlainn in 1022 and the chaos which accompanied the subsequent bids for the High Kingship by the Irish princes, Sigtrygg Silkbeard was forced to make a new alliance with the men of [[Kings of Brega|Brega]].<ref>Hudson, p 109-110</ref> Amlaíb joined Donnchad of Brega in a raid on Staholmock, County Meath.<ref name="Hudson110">Hudson, p 110</ref> The army of Sigtrygg and Donnchad was defeated by the men of Meath under their [[Kings of Mide|king]], Roen Ua Mael Sechlainn.<ref name="Hudson110"/><ref name="Annals13-815">{{cite web |url=http://www.ucc.ie/celt/online/T100005B/text013.html |title=Part 13 of the Annals of the Four Masters |publisher=[[University College Cork]] |work=[[Annals of the Four Masters]] |page=815 |accessdate=10 March 2009 }}</ref> Sigtrygg rallied to the fight again, and fought a battle at Lickblaw where Donnchad and Roen were slain.<ref name="Hudson110"/><ref name="Annals13-815"/>
In 1029, Amlaíb was taken prisoner by the new [[Kings of Brega|lord of Brega]], Mathghamhain Ua Riagain, who exacted a ransom of 1200 cows.<ref name="Annals13-819"/> Further conditions of the agreement necessitated payment of another 140 British horses, 60 ounces of gold and of silver, "the sword of Carlus", the Irish [[hostage]]s of Leinster and [[Leath Cuinn]], "four hostages to Ua Riagain as a security for peace, and the full value of the life of the third hostage."<ref name="Annals13-819"/> Added to the total, 80 cows "for word and [[supplication]]"<ref name="Annals13-819"/> were to be paid to the man who entreated for Amlaíb's release.<ref name="Hudson111">Hudson, p 111</ref> The incident illustrates the importance of ransoming noble captives, as a means of political manipulation, increasing one's own revenues and exhausting the resources of one's foes.<ref name="Hudson111"/> The demand of British horses also suggests that Dublin was one of the main ports for importing horses into 11th century Ireland, and that Amlaíb's family may have been personally involved in [[Animal husbandry|husbandry]].<ref name="Hudson111"/>
According to the 17th century ''[[Annals of the Four Masters]]'', Amlaíb mac Sitriuc "was slain by the [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxons]]" on his way on a pilgrimage to Rome in 1034.<ref name="Annals14-831">{{cite web |url=http://www.ucc.ie/celt/online/T100005B/text014.html |title=Part 14 of the Annals of the Four Masters |publisher=[[University College Cork]] |work=[[Annals of the Four Masters]] |page=831 |accessdate=10 March 2009 }}</ref> He was survived by one Ragnhild, who was the mother of [[Gruffudd ap Cynan]], from whom the [[Kings of Gwynedd]] were descended.<ref name="Hudson83"/>
