{{Infobox person |image = |imagesize = | name = Jules Greenbaum | birth_date = 15 January 1867 | birth_place = [[Berlin]], [[Kingdom of Prussia]] | birth_name = Julius Grünbaum | death_date = 1 November 1924 (aged 57) | death_place = Berlin, [[German Empire]] | children = [[Mutz Greenbaum]] | occupation = [[Film producer]] | yearsactive = [[1899 in film|1899]]–[[1921 in film|1921]] }} '''Jules Greenbaum''' (5 January 1867 – 1 November 1924) was a German pioneering [[film producer]]. He founded the production companies Deutsche Bioscope, Deutsche Vitascope and Greenbaum-Film{{sfn|Bock|Bergfelder|2009|pp=166–7}} and was a dominant figure in [[Cinema of Germany|German cinema]] in the years before the [[First World War]]. He is also known for his early experiments with [[sound film]]s around twenty years before the success of ''[[The Jazz Singer]]'' made them a more established feature of cinema.
==Early career and Deutsche Bioscope== Greenbaum was born in Berlin in 1867 as Julius Grünbaum. He married Emma Karstein in c1887 and moved to [[Chicago]] in the [[United States]], where his first son Georg was born 1 November 1889.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}} He originally worked in the [[textile]] industry, but on his return to Berlin in 1895 aged around 42 Greenbaum moved into the newly established film business and founded Deutsche Bioscope ({{lang-de|Deutsche Bioskop}}) in 1899.{{sfn|Bock|Bergfelder|2009|pp=166}} Greenbaum acquired a camera in Amsterdam, and a cameraman, Georg Furkel. Furkel worked as his technical director until 1912, along with another Dutch cameraman, Martin Knoop.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}
Deutsche Bioscope's first independent film was the 60-metre 1899 newsreel picture ''Spring Parade'' featuring German Kaiser [[Wilhelm II of Germany|Wilhelm II]]. His firm released more newsreels in 1901/02, importing American and French features and manufacturing cinema equipment.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}
Deutsche Bioscope GmbH, Berlin, was incorporated on 18 June 1902 with a capital of 20,000 marks<ref>Entry in the Commercial Register {Handelsregister} 23 June 1902 {{harv|Hampicke|2015|}}.</ref> The main offices were at 131d [[Friedrichstraße]], where the firm supplied equipment (including the American Biograph camera), and an 8-hour guaranteed film copying service. Bioscope's cameramen were sent to Vienna, Munich, Leipzig, Halle, Nuremberg, Kiel, Hamburg, Poznan, Lviv and Riga in search of vaudeville/variety acts to film.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}
'''Studios at 123 Chausseestraße'''
[[File:Berlin, Mitte, Chausseestrasse 123, Wohn- und Geschaeftshaus.jpg|thumb|123 Chauseestraße]] Bioscope built new offices in 1906 at 123 [[Chausseestraße]], in the east of Berlin; a glasshouse studio was erected in the large courtyard at the rear of the [[Jugendstil]] building, where [[Continental-Kunstfilm]] would later film ''[[In Nacht und Eis]]'' in 1912.<ref name=Bioscope-Atelier>{{cite web |title=Bioscope-Atelier |url=http://www.cinegraph.de/etc/ateliers/bioskop.html |work=Berliner Film-Ateliers. Ein kleines Lexikon. |series=Lexikon zum deutschsprachigen Film. (Online edition of {{harvnb|Berg-Ganschow|Jacobsen|1987|pp=177–202}}) |publisher=Cinegraph.de |accessdate=31 July 2015 |language=German}}</ref>
'''Vitascope-Theater'''
Greenbaum began acquiring [[cinemas]], opening a Vitascope cinema at 10 Friedrichstraße,<ref group=n>Coincidentally, right next door<!-- (or right opposite, depends on the numbering) --> to 11 Friedrichstraße, the offices of Cines-Theater AG, a Berlin-based offshoot of the [[Società Italiana Cines]], which was involved with the building of the [[Ufa-Pavillon am Nollendorfplatz]] in 1912–1913.</ref> and in March 1907 he registered Vitascope Theater GmbH as a limited company. Its partners were Louis Rosenfeld and Otto Heinemann.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}} This established a [[vertical integration|vertically integrated]] network with Vitascope handling the [[film distribution|distribution]] for Bioscope films.
'''Sale of Deutsche Bioscope'''
As his business increased, Greenbaum made a deal with the chemist Carl Moritz Schleussner of the photochemicals firm Schleussner AG in [[Frankfurt am Main|Frankfurt/Main]]. Carl Schleussner had been involved since 1896 in producing negative film stock for [[X-ray photography|Röntgen photography]] soon after its discovery.<ref name=Eisenbach>Eisenbach, Ulrich, (2007).[http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/ppn131435329.html ''Schleussner'' in: Neue Deutsche Biographie 23 , pp. 68–69 [Online edition] (in German).</ref> In February 1908 Carl Schleussner bought Deutsche Bioscop as a manufacturing, copying and sales operation, for a 2/3 share of 140,000 marks, with 1/3 provided by Greenbaum and his brother Max. Deutsche Bioscop was re-registered on 27 February 1908, and Schleussner bought out the Greenbaums' remaining share in 1909.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}} Under its new owner, Deutsche Bioscope moved to [[Babelsberg Studio]] in November 1911, which is well-known as the oldest large-scale film studio in the world and still today producing famous [[Blockbuster (entertainment)|Blockbusters]].<ref name=Babelsberg>{{cite web |title=Babelsberg |url=http://www.cinegraph.de/etc/ateliers/babelsberg.html |work=Berliner Film-Ateliers. Ein kleines Lexikon. |series=Lexikon zum deutschsprachigen Film. (Online edition of {{harvnb|Berg-Ganschow|Jacobsen|1987|pp=177–202}}) |publisher=Cinegraph.de |accessdate=31 July 2015 |language=German |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904040034/http://www.cinegraph.de/etc/ateliers/babelsberg.html |archivedate= 4 September 2014 |df= }}</ref>
'''Bioscope-Theater'''
Greenbaum registered a new cinema company, Bioscope-Theater GmbH, on 24 Feb 1908.<ref group=n>This seems to have been changed to Vitascope-Theater at some point.</ref> The directors were Jules' brother, Max Greenbaum (an experienced banker), and Erich Zeiske.<ref>There is a photo of Zeiske (among many others) at the first International Congress of Film Manufacturers in Paris in February 1909. See {{cite web |title=International Meetings and Congresses of Film Manufacturers held in Paris, 1908-1909: French Viewpoints |last=Meusy |first=Jean-Jacques (n.d.) |url=https://www.academia.edu/22873827/INTERNATIONAL_MEETINGS_AND_CONGRESSES_OF_THE_FILM_MANUFACTURERS_HELD_IN_PARIS_1908-1909._FRENCH_VIEWPOINTS |accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref> In October 1908, Greenbaum opened the {{ill|Rollkrug|de}} Vitascope cinema, a showpiece 500-seat movie theatre on {{ill|Hermannplatz|de}}, 1–2 Berliner Straße.
==Synchroscope – early sound films== Greenbaum's firm invented and used [[Synchroscope (technology)|Synchroscope]], which synchronised the visual picture of films with [[phonograph]] records to create a working sound and vision system. Greenbaum produced a number of these sound shorts of vocal classical music, and in 1908 entered into contracts to supply the machinery to [[Carl Laemmle]]'s Movie Service Company in Chicago and to another American, [[Charles Urban]], in Britain.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}} [[Carl Laemmle]] installed the system in a number of American cinemas, mostly in German-speaking communities.<ref name="Eyman p.29">Eyman p.29</ref> Synchroscope largely petered out because not enough sound films were made to meet demand and because it could only last for two or three [[reels]] while the standard length of films was increasingly four or five reels long.<ref name="Eyman p.29"/> Costs had soared by the end of 1908 (the Synchroscope was originally priced at $750 (around $20,000 in 2015);<ref name="Eyman p.29"/> and Schleussner AG bought out Greenbaum's share of Deutsche Bioscope to free up his operations.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}
==Deutsche Vitascope== On 8 September 1909 Vitascope-Theater GmbH changed its name to Deutsche Vitascope GmbH, with Greenbaum the owner and managing director, and headquarters at 20 Friedrichstraße. The firm's chief objective was the production of sound pictures on continuous film so that all the reels could be shown without interruptions.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}} The 1910 Vitascope catalogue advertised a flicker-free camera, Vitaphone soundfilms, arc lamps, used original Vitascope films and 100,000 meters of used [[vaudeville]]/variety act movies, for 20-40 pfennigs/meter.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}
{{Anchor|Lindenstraße}} '''Studios at 32–34 Lindenstraße'''
In 1910 Vitascope opened main offices and a film copying facility at 32–34 {{ill|Lindenstraße (berlin)|de|Lindenstraße (Berlin-Kreuzberg)|lt=Lindenstraße}}, with a glasshouse studio on the roof. Greenbaum moved to new recording rooms for sound production at 105 [[Große Frankfurter Straße]], where Vitascope produced short films of about 120 feet (60m) synchronised with phonograph recordings of vocal numbers, opera arias and dance pieces. The sound films were directed by [[Franz Porten]] and starred his daughter [[Henny Porten]]. One notable film was of ''[[Mignon]]'' Act I by [[Ambroise Thomas]] with the [[Staatskapelle Berlin|Royal Court Orchestra]] & Choir and the Royal Ballet.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}<ref>The orchestra's conductor from 1899 to 1913 was [[Richard Strauss]].</ref>
Greenbaum also had a 'normal' silent film studio at 94 Markgrafenstraße. Vitascope's first film of 1910 was ''[[Arsène Lupin contra Sherlock Holmes]]'' produced and directed by [[Viggo Larsen]] who joined in 1909 from [[Nordisk Film|Nordisk]]. Larsen remained with Vitascope for two years, then founded his own company with star Wanda Treumann. [[Continental-Kunstfilm|Walter Schmidthässler]] also joined in 1910, working as director and lead actor for Vitascope.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}} In 1911 [[Max Mack]] was engaged as scriptwriter, soon debuting as actor and director, with ''Gehirnreflexe'' (Brain Reflex) and three others with [[Albert Bassermann]], notably ''[[The Other (1913 film)|The Other]]''.{{sfn|Bock|Bergfelder|2009|pp=166–7}} ''[[The Blue Mouse (1913 film)|The Blue Mouse]]'' showed at the new [[Marmorhaus]] cinema.
{{Anchor|Friedrichstraße}} '''Studio at 16 Friedrichstraße'''
Vitascope opened a further studio at [[Friedrichstraße]] 16 in 1911; and in October 1912 Greenbaum vacated 123 Chauseestraße and moved everything to 32–34 Lindenstraße (including manufacture, developing and copying equipment). The fine red sandstone building at 123 Chauseestraße was taken over by Walter Schmidthässler and his recently formed [[Continental-Kunstfilm]].<ref name=Vitascope-Atelier>{{cite web |title=Vitascope-Atelier |url=http://www.cinegraph.de/etc/ateliers/vitascope.html |work=Berliner Film-Ateliers. Ein kleines Lexikon. |series=Lexikon zum deutschsprachigen Film. (Online edition of {{harvnb|Berg-Ganschow|Jacobsen|1987|pp=177–202}}) |publisher=Cinegraph.de |accessdate=31 July 2015 |language=German}}</ref><ref name=May-Atelier>{{cite web |title=May-Atelier |url=http://www.cinegraph.de/etc/ateliers/may.html |work=Berliner Film-Ateliers. Ein kleines Lexikon. |publisher=Cinegraph.de |series=Lexikon zum deutschsprachigen Film. (Online edition of {{harvnb|Berg-Ganschow|Jacobsen|1987|pp=177–202}}) |accessdate=31 July 2015 |language=German}}</ref>{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}
{{Anchor|Weissensee}} '''Studios at 5–7 Franz-Josef-Straße, Weissensee'''
Needing to expand even further, Greenbaum acquired land at 5–7 Franz-Josef-Straße (now Max-Liebermann-Straße), [[Weißensee (Berlin)|Weißensee]], and in 1913 built a double glasshouse studio along with the largest film processing lab in the country (capable of an advertised 100,000 meters daily capacity.) Showrooms remained in 32/34 Lindenstraße, and the entire production of films moved to Weissensee on 1 October 1913, along with the manufacturing, drying and copying equipment.<ref name=May-Atelier />{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}{{refn|group=n|The studios at 32/34 Lindenstraße were briefly occupied in 1928 by a less successful [[sound film]] company, Lignose Hörfilm System Breusing GmbH.<ref name=Vitascope-Atelier /> The parent company, Lignose AG, processed [[nitrates]], producing raw [[celluloid]] film, along with [[guncotton]] and other explosives, and pocket pistols.<ref>Buffaloe, E. (2015). [http://unblinkingeye.com/Guns/Lignose/lignose.html The Bergmann and Lignose Pocket and Vestpocket Pistols]. Unblinkingeye.com. Retrieved 30 July 2015.</ref> Along with a film production company, Phoebus AG, Lignose was indirectly involved in a hushed-up scandal which had threatened to expose wide-spread circumvention of the terms of the [[Versailles Treaty]] by Germany after [[World War I]]. The "Lohmann Affair" was named after the Naval Captain ({{lang-de|Kapitan zur See}}) who oversaw millions of marks' worth of clandestine funding for secret Naval projects during the [[Weimar Republic]].<ref>CIA Report: [https://www.cia.gov/library/center-for-the-study-of-intelligence/kent-csi/vol4no2/html/v04i2a08p_0001.htm ''The Lohmann Affair'']. Studies in Intelligence'', Vol. 4, No. 2 (Spring 1960). [[Central Intelligence Agency]], pp. A31-A38. (Declassified in 1993)</ref>}}
==Merger with PAGU== In January 1914 Greenbaum merged his Vitascope firm with [[PAGU]] (Projektions-Aktiengesellschaft 'Union'), owned by his rival [[Paul Davidson (producer)|Paul Davidson]], in order to compete with the larger French studios who were flooding the German market with their films.{{sfn|Bock|Bergfelder|2009|pp=166–7}} PAGU combined the resources of 800 employees, with main offices in Zimmerstraße and Lindenstraße, 20 "Union" cinemas, glasshouse studios in Tempelhof and in Weissensee, with its duplicating lab. Both companies continued to produce films under their own name and logos. From January 1914 [[Richard Oswald]] was artistic and advertising director at Vitascope. Oswald made the "Baskerville" detective series.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}
'''Pathé'''
Still seeking further distribution outlets, Greenbaum and Davidson closed a deal with [[Pathé|Pathé Frères]] to distribute PAGU films.{{sfn|Bock|Bergfelder|2009|pp=166–7}} Pathé bought the Weissensee studios at 5–7 Franz-Josef-Straße in July 1914. However, with the outbreak of the [[First World War]], foreign films were barred from Germany allowing domestic production to boom. Pathé and PAGU broke off relationships; the admin offices and studios belonging to Pathé were placed into receivership, and reverted to Greenbaum.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}
==Greenbaum-Film== '''Weissensee'''
Freed by the war from the foreign competition, Greenbaum broke with Davidson's PAGU and founded Greenbaum-Film out of Vitascope.{{sfn|Bock|Bergfelder|2009|pp=166}} On 12 January 1915 Greenbaum-Film was incorporated with 10,000 marks and started production again in 5–7 Franz-Josef-Straße, Weissensee, with office and sales at Friedrichstraße 235. An article in ''Lichtbild-Bühne'' for 3 June 1915 announced: "Dr. Hans Oberländer, Richard Löwenbein, Richard Oswald, Greenbaum-Film GmbH – the biggest film factory in Germany." Oswald made five films in a few months and then separated financially from Greenbaum-Film, becoming a self-employed producer and director.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}
In 1916 Greenbaum closed a deal with [[Albert Bassermann]], who starred in seventeen films for Greenbaum-Film by 1920. The director Adolf Gärtner (who worked on [[Joe May]]'s [[Stuart Webbs]] detective series) also moved to Greenbaum-Film and directed nine films in Weißensee. Greenbaum took out a 5-year lease on the Weißensee premises from 4 January 1917 – 1922. In 1919 he leased the double glasshouse studios to [[Joe May]] for 600,000 marks, which became known as the May-Atelier.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}
==Merger with Ufa – bankruptcy and death== In 1919 Greenbaum affiliated with [[Universum Film AG|Ufa]], which the State had quietly established as the giant of German film industry during the war,{{sfn|Nowell-Smith|1996|p=92}} but the deal led to a series of legal disputes and the virtual bankruptcy of Greenbaum-Film. Greenbaum had a monopoly contract with Ufa to supply films to Ukraine, Bulgaria, Romania and Turkey. Despite the political events in the Balkans, Ufa claimed millions from Greenbaum for lost sales and the dispute escalated through the courts. Ufa's interests were represented by Hemann Fellner, Greenbaum's former business partner.{{sfn|Hampicke|2015|}}
Greenbaum lost the factory and everything else, and died in 1924 in a mental hospital aged 57. The studios were taken over by Ufa after his death; his two sons George and [[Mutz Greenbaum|Mutz]] managed Greenbaum-Film until it was taken over by Hermann Millakowsky and eventually liquidated in 1932.{{sfn|Bock|Bergfelder|2009|pp=166–7}}
During his life Greenbaum launched the career of a number of leading German directors and actors including [[Max Mack]], [[Richard Oswald]] and [[Maria Orska]]. His son [[Mutz Greenbaum]] ("Max Greene") became a leading [[cinematographer]], whose films include [[Christopher Columbus (1923 film)]] starring Albert Bassermann, [[Thunder Rock (film)|Thunder Rock]] (1942) and [[I'm All Right Jack]] (1959).
==Selected filmography== * ''[[The Other (1913 film)|The Other]]'' (1913) * ''[[The Blue Mouse (1913 film)|The Blue Mouse]]'' (1913) * ''[[Where Is Coletti?]]'' (1913) * ''[[Detektiv Braun]]'' (1914) * ''{{ill|Ivan Koschula|de}}'' (1914) * ''{{ill|Dämon und Mensch|it}}'' (1915, producer)
