{{Euthanasia}}
{{Globalize|date=November 2014}}
'''Non-voluntary euthanasia''' is [[euthanasia]] conducted when the explicit [[consent]] of the [[individual]] concerned is unavailable, such as when the person is in a [[persistent vegetative state]], or [[child euthanasia|in the case of young children]].<ref>[http://www.buzzle.com/articles/mercy-killing-facts.html Mercy killing facts]. Buzzle.</ref> It contrasts with [[Involuntary euthanasia|''involuntary'' euthanasia]], when euthanasia is performed ''against'' the will of the patient.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Perrett RW |title=Buddhism, euthanasia and the sanctity of life |journal=J Med Ethics |volume=22 |issue=5 |pages=309–13 |date=October 1996 |pmid=8910785 |pmc=1377066 |doi=10.1136/jme.22.5.309}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author=LaFollette, Hugh |title=Ethics in practice: an anthology |publisher=Blackwell |location=Oxford |year=2002 |pages=25–26 |isbn=0-631-22834-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o5peQpgSTTIC&pg=RA1-PA3-IA1}}</ref>

<!--expand this paragraph using the Hazel Biggs book -->
The different possible situations considered non-voluntary euthanasia are when the decision to end the life of the patient is 1) based on what the incapacitated individual would have wanted if they could be asked, 2) based on what the decision maker would want if he or she were in the patient's place, and 3) made by a doctor based on their own criteria and reasoning.<ref name="euthanasia_a23">{{Cite book| last1 = Biggs | first1 = Hazel | title = Euthanasia: Death with Dignity and the Law | date =  | publisher = Hart Publishing | location =  | isbn = 1-84113-091-5 | pages =  }}</ref>

==Legal status==
{{Main|Legality of euthanasia}}
Euthanasia can all be  divided into passive or active variants.<ref>{{Cite journal |doi=10.1056/NEJM197501092920206 |author=Rachels J |title=Active and passive euthanasia |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=292 |issue=2 |pages=78–80 |date=January 1975 |pmid=1109443 |url=http://content.nejm.org/cgi/content/short/292/2/78 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100630114314/http://content.nejm.org/cgi/content/short/292/2/78 |archivedate=2010-06-30 |df= }}</ref> Passive euthanasia entails the withholding of common treatments, such as antibiotics, necessary for the continuance of life.<ref name="Harris-2001"/> Active euthanasia entails the use of lethal substances or forces, such as administering a [[lethal injection]], to kill and is the most controversial means. A number of authors consider these terms to be misleading and unhelpful.<ref name="Harris-2001">{{Cite journal| last1 = Harris| first1 = NM.| title = The euthanasia debate| journal = J R Army Med Corps | volume = 147| issue = 3| pages = 367–70|date=Oct 2001| pmid = 11766225| doi=10.1136/jramc-147-03-22}}</ref>

''Active'' non-voluntary euthanasia is illegal in all countries in the world, although it is practised in the Netherlands on infants (see below) under an agreement between physicians and district attorneys.<ref name="origin">{{Cite web |url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/569471 |title=Ending the Life of a Newborn: The Groningen Protocol,: Introduction |publisher=www.medscape.com |accessdate=2009-11-03 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101109180336/http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/569471 |archivedate=2010-11-09 |df= }}</ref> ''Passive'' non-voluntary euthanasia (withholding life support) is legal in various countries, such as India, Albania, and many parts of the United States and is practiced in English hospitals.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article1516973.ece| location=Chennai, India| work=The Hindu| title=India joins select nations in legalising "passive euthanasia"| date=7 March 2011| deadurl=no| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110311130458/http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article1516973.ece| archivedate=11 March 2011| df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ajrccm.atsjournals.org/cgi/content/full/162/6/2029 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-03-09 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120701143528/http://ajrccm.atsjournals.org/cgi/content/full/162/6/2029 |archivedate=2012-07-01 |df= }}</ref>

Non-voluntary euthanasia has been heavily debated. For example, [[Len Doyal]], a professor of medical ethics and former member of the ethics committee of the [[British Medical Association]], argued for legalization, saying in 2006 that "[p]roponents of voluntary euthanasia should support non-voluntary euthanasia under appropriate circumstances and with proper regulation".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/5056326.stm |title='Legalise euthanasia' says expert |date=8 June 2006 |newspaper=[[BBC News Online]] |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403143938/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/5056326.stm |archivedate=3 April 2012 |df= }}</ref> Arguing against legalization, Peter Saunders, campaign director for [[Care Not Killing]], an alliance of [[Christian]] and [[disability]] groups, called Doyal's proposals "the very worst form of medical paternalism whereby doctors can end the lives of patients after making a judgment that their lives are of no value and claim that they are simply acting in their patients' best interests".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2006/jun/08/health.medicineandhealth1 |title=Call for no-consent euthanasia |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=8 June 2006 |first=Sarah |last=Boseley |location=London |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225205905/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2006/jun/08/health.medicineandhealth1 |archivedate=25 February 2017 |df= }}</ref>

==Slippery slope debate==
{{main|Euthanasia and the slippery slope}}
Non-voluntary euthanasia is cited as one of the possible outcomes of the [[Euthanasia and the slippery slope|slippery slope argument against euthanasia]], in which it is claimed that permitting voluntary euthanasia to occur will lead to the support and legalization of non-voluntary and [[involuntary euthanasia]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Voluntary Euthanasia|url=http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/euthanasia-voluntary/#Six|work=Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|publisher=Stanford University|accessdate=June 13, 2010|date=March 29, 2010}}</ref> although other ethicists have contested this idea.<ref name="Lewis-2007">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Lewis | first1 = P. | title = The empirical slippery slope from voluntary to non-voluntary euthanasia. | journal = J Law Med Ethics | volume = 35 | issue = 1 | pages = 197–210 | month =  | year = 2007 | doi = 10.1111/j.1748-720X.2007.00124.x | pmid = 17341228 }}</ref><ref name="Ryan-1998">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Ryan | first1 = CJ. | title = Pulling up the runaway: the effect of new evidence on euthanasia's slippery slope. | journal = J Med Ethics | volume = 24 | issue = 5 | pages = 341–4 |date=Oct 1998 | doi =  10.1136/jme.24.5.341 | pmid=9800591 | pmc=1377611}}</ref><ref name="Manninen-2006">{{Cite journal  | last1 = Manninen | first1 = BA. | title = A case for justified non-voluntary active euthanasia: exploring the ethics of the Groningen Protocol. | journal = J Med Ethics | volume = 32 | issue = 11 | pages = 643–51 |date=Nov 2006 | doi = 10.1136/jme.2005.014845 | pmid=17074822 | pmc=2563300}}</ref>

==Non-voluntary euthanasia in the Netherlands==
[[File:Hydrocephalus-baby.jpg|thumb|float|right|200px|Severe [[hydrocephalus]]. Infants like this can be subject to non-voluntary euthanasia in the [[Netherlands]] if the parents and doctors decide it is the best choice for their child. In other jurisdictions, the doctors involved may be prosecuted.]]
{{main|Euthanasia in the Netherlands|Groningen protocol}}
Permitted euthanasia in the Netherlands has been regulated by law since 2002. It states that euthanasia and physician-assisted suicide are not punishable if the attending physician acts in accordance with criteria of due care.<ref name="Buiting-2009">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Buiting H, van Delden J, Onwuteaka-Philpsen B, etal |title=Reporting of euthanasia and physician-assisted suicide in the Netherlands: descriptive study |journal=BMC Med Ethics |volume=10 |issue= |pages=18 |year=2009 |pmid=19860873 |pmc=2781018 |doi=10.1186/1472-6939-10-18}}</ref> Prior to the establishment of that law, euthanasia and assisted suicide in the Netherlands were already tolerated for many years, as for example described by G. van der Wal and R. J. Dillmann in 1994.<ref name=Dillmann>{{cite journal|author1=van der Wal, G. |author2=R. J. Dillmann |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Euthanasia in the Netherlands|journal=British Medical Journal|year=1994|volume=308|issue=6940|pages=1346–1349|doi=10.1136/bmj.308.6940.1346}}</ref> In a 1994 study, of the studied 5000 requests in the Netherlands, in about 1000 of the cases, doctors prescribed drugs with the explicit goal of shortening the patient's life without the explicit request of the patient, which can be considered cases of non-voluntary euthanasia.<ref name=Dillmann/><ref name=Fleming>{{cite journal|last=Fleming|first=John|title=Euthanasia, The Netherlands, and Slippery Slopes|journal=Bioethics Notes Research Occasional Paper|date=June 1992|issue=1}}</ref>

Since 2004, the [[Netherlands]], also has a protocol to be followed in cases of euthanasia on children under the age of 12 (see also below), which was ratified by the Dutch National Association of Pediatricians, although the practice remains technically illegal. Together with colleagues and prosecutors, [[Eduard Verhagen]] developed the [[Groningen Protocol]], in which cases [[prosecutor]]s will refrain from pressing charges.<ref>
{{Cite news|last1=Verhagen|first1=Eduard|last2=Sauer|first2=Pieter J.J.|year=2005|title=The Groningen Protocol — Euthanasia in Severely Ill Newborns|periodical=[[The New England Journal of Medicine]]|volume=352|issue=10|pages=959–962|url=|doi=10.1056/NEJMp058026|pmid=15758003|postscript=<!--none-->}}</ref><ref>
{{Cite web|title=Outrage from Churches over Euthanasia on Newborns|date=December 1, 2004|url=http://www.ekklesia.co.uk/content/news_syndication/article_04121eut.shtml|accessdate=2007-05-22|postscript=<!--none-->|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928074528/http://www.ekklesia.co.uk/content/news_syndication/article_04121eut.shtml|archivedate=September 28, 2007|df=}}</ref>

==Non-voluntary euthanasia on children==
{{Main|Child euthanasia}}

===Newborns and euthanasia===
Active euthanasia on newborns is illegal throughout the world, with the ''de facto'' exception of the Netherlands mentioned above. Because a newborn child is never able to speak for themselves, euthanasia on newborns is by definition non-voluntary. An early example of documented cases of child euthanasia are [[Child euthanasia#Harry Haiselden and Baby Bollinger|those performed]] by the surgeon [[Harry J. Haiselden]] in Chicago in the early 20th century.

===Ancient Greece===
{{main|History of eugenics#Pre-Galtonian philosophies}}
In ancient Greece, non-voluntary euthanasia of children was practiced as an early form of [[eugenics]], the belief and practice of improving the genetic quality of the human population, usually by withdrawing care (i.e. passive euthanasia) rather than a physical extermination, an act termed as “exposure”.<ref name=Patterson>{{cite journal|last=Patterson|first=Cynthia|title="Not Worth the Rearing": Causes of Infant Exposure in Ancient Greece|journal=Transactions of the American Philological Association|year=1985|volume=115|pages=111–123}}</ref>

